{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642/events","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642","id":1092196573,"node_id":"I_kwDOABkWpM5BGZjd","number":43642,"title":"Index sets and constant propagation on Array shapes","user":{"login":"ChrisRackauckas","id":1814174,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE4MTQxNzQ=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1814174?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas","html_url":"https://github.com/ChrisRackauckas","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ChrisRackauckas/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":4,"created_at":"2022-01-03T03:29:28Z","updated_at":"2022-01-03T14:21:54Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"It's not too uncommon for type computations to be determined by the size of arrays. One case is ForwardDiff chunksize computations. Another are the algorithm defaults in DifferentialEquations.jl. While these do not necessarily effect runtime performance because the computations lie behind function barriers, they seem to greatly effect compile-time performance and thus were the impetus for compile-time features such as https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/43370. 

Such usage of max_methods=1 and function barriers could be completed eliminated if constant propagation could perform shape inference, moving chunk size computations to compile time. Even further, it has been shown that having index set information as part of the type can be very powerful for optimizations, parallelization, and automatic differentiation (https://arxiv.org/abs/2104.05372). That said, extending the type parameters of an Array would be breaking and thus require a v2.0, while adding constant propagation to array shape calculations would not necessarily be and thus I would probably be leaning towards the latter. Of course, it could be possible that shape calculations are so much more expensive that it actually hurts the compile time in that case as well.

But there's probably some other places where shape inference could help improve GC performance, make odd compilation targets easier for shape-inferable code (like static compilation), etc. so I was curious to see whether this would/could be something done as part of the language itself or whether this would be left to AbstractInterpreter plugins.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1004125822","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642#issuecomment-1004125822","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43642","id":1004125822,"node_id":"IC_kwDOABkWpM472b5-","user":{"login":"jpsamaroo","id":17912843,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE3OTEyODQz","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/17912843?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo","html_url":"https://github.com/jpsamaroo","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/jpsamaroo/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-01-03T14:21:54Z","updated_at":"2022-01-03T14:21:54Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"I believe the start of this is https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/43487 (although I'm not sure if it calculates total shape; it seems like it might just be `ndims` for now). From there, it's a matter of ensuring that functions like `similar`, and operations like array slicing, also propagate the sizes of their returns, which is probably rather simple to determine by forwarding allocation shape to `length`/`size` calls (which are often used to determine the size of the new output array to allocate).","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1004125822/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

